1 Rationale and Research Questions

Urban coastal ecosystems are sensitive to stormwater runoff, which is rain water and waste water that flows over streets, sidewalks, and other surfaces. It picks up debris, oil, fertilizers, and other pollutants along the way before entering the stormwater system. The system is designed to drain cities of rain water and help minimize flooding. As a result, carries and deposits polluted runoff into surrounding waterways, causing harm to nearby ecossytems. Unfortunately, this is the case for Biscayne Bay near the City of Miami Beach. To address such issues, Miami-Dade County implemented an ordinance that prohibits the use of fertilizers containing nitrogen and phosphorus during the summer rainy season. The ordinance was passed in January, 2021, and was adopted in April of the same year. The ordinance is effective from May 15 through October 31 every year (accounting for raining season).

This study examines whether measurable changes in nutrient concentrations or related indicators appeared following the implementation of the Miami-Dade County fertilizer ordinance by using data from the City of Miami Beach Water Monitoring Program. The goal is to quantify these changes through time series and statistical analyses. We chose to look at this specific dataset because it includes measurements for multiple years, and it is specific to the location that we are looking to assess. It also measures parameters that are crucial to our analyses, such as total nitrogen, total phosphorus, dissolved oxygen, and pH.

4 Analysis

4.1 Question 1: How do the pre- and post-ordinance trends in monthly averages compare in terms of A) Total Phosphorous, B) Total Nitrogen, C) Dissolved Oxygen, and D) pH?

4.1.1 Pre- vs.Post-Ordinance Monthly Trend Analysis

(#fig:pre vs post TS)Comparing Pre- and Post-Ordinance Trends in Water Quality Parameters


Table 4.1: Results Summary of Pre- and Post-Ordinance Monthly Averages
Pre.Ordinance_Z.Stat Pre.Ordinance_p.value Post.Ordinance_Z.Stat Post.Ordinance_p.value
Total_Phosphorous 1.312 0.190 -2.544 0.011
Total_Nitrogen -1.929 0.054 -0.848 0.396
Dissolved_Oxygen -0.694 0.487 -1.696 0.090
pH 0.231 0.817 -2.332 0.020

We conducted monthly time series analysis of the various parameters to assess whether monotonic trends differed before and after the implementation of the ordinance. The dashed vertical line in these plots represent the ordinance implementation time. Seasonal Mann-Kendall (SMK) tests were applied separately to pre- and post-ordinance periods to evaluate the presence of statistically significant monotonic trends while accounting for seasonality (Figure xx).

Time series analysis reveals statistically significant, downward monotonic trends in post-ordinance Total Phosphorous (SMK; z < 0, p-value < 0.05) and pH (SMK; z < 0, p-value < 0.05). For both parameters, no significant trend was observed prior to the ordinance implementation. For the other two parameters, dissolved oxygen and pH, plotted time series trends show some variability, but no pre- or post-ordinance variables showed significant monotonic trends. SMK results for all parameters are summarized in Table __.

4.1.2 Comparison of Monthly and Yearly Trends

To assess whether the interpolated monthly observation reflect accurate description of the data, we created plots that show trend of the yearly mean value for the different parameters between 2016 and 2025 (Figure xx). For all parameters, yearly averages maintained the direction and relative magnitude of post-ordinance changes observed earlier in the monthly data.

To compare the results in a more visual way, we stacked the monthly and yearly plots to assess their trends for each of the parameters. For all four parameters, the monthly and yearly plots seem to follow similar trends. The yearly mean total phosphorus concentrations show a clear decline beginning in 2021, which is consistent with the significant post-ordinance monotonic trend we identified earlier in monthly analyses. The yearly mean total nitrogen presented larger variability regarding trends throughout the years, but its general trend had a declining direction after 2021. The yearly mean dissolved oxygen had large spikes during the early times and showed limited differentiation after ordinance implementation, while the yearly mean pH showed a modest decline following 2021.

The similar plot patterns between the monthly and yearly time series suggest that the observed post-ordinance declines in phosphorous and pH are consistent across time scales, while nitrogen and dissolved oxygen show high variability in both datasets.

One-way analysis of variance (ANOVA) was performed on the four study parameters using year as a categorical variable to calculate means. Analysis of Total Phosphorous (df = 8, F = 36.18, p < 0.00001) and Total Nitrogen (df = 8, F = 3.554, p < 0.005) found statistically significant differences among the yearly means for both parameters. There were no statistically significant differences among yearly means for Dissolved Oxygen (df = 8, F = 1.04, p = 0.413) or pH (df = 8, F = 1.648, p = 0.124).

These results indicate that there are relatively stronger shifts between years in nutrient concentrations, particularly for phosphorous. On the other hand, physical water quality parameters presented weaker and more variable year-to-year differentiation.

Following ANOVA, Tukeys honestly significant difference test (HSD) was used to identify years with diverging means across variables. The results are summarized in Table __. Yearly Total Phosphorous means were more stratified, with seven years belonging to single, distinct mean groups. One statistically unique mean group occurs only before 2021, a second occurs only during 2021, and a third occurs only afterward. Total Nitrogen also showed statistically distinct mean groups occurring before and after 2021 but had less separation overall. Both parameters showed less separation among mean groups in 2017 and 2018. For dissolved oxygen and pH, the results indicated substantial overlap among yearly mean groups, which reinforce the earlier ANOVA results that suggested limited year-to-year differences for these parameters.
